at will reconfigure the critical uses of spectrality for scholars in U.S./Latin American Studies, narrative theory, and comparative literature, Blanco advances ghost-watching as a method for rediscovering haunting on its own terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aComparative literaturexAmerican and Latin American. 0aComparative literaturexLatin American and American. 0aGhosts in literature. 0aHaunted places. 0aLandscapes in literature. 0aNationalism in literature. 0aSpanish American literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLatin American Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aLatin American Literature.  aU.S. Literature.  aghosts.  ahaunting.  alandscape.  amodernity.  aspace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823242177zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823242177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823242177/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK